Skeptical of the crowd consensus. Although updating the recent falls into Bayes' theorem leads to a still >80% probabilities of the event not occuring, I am lower in my forecast reasoning. If you remove the extreme ups and downs, you see a consistent fall or even slight plateau in the trend. Morever, looking up different questionsâ€”including cryptocurrency questionsâ€”in GJO's question's lookup, I can see that those users who placed too much weight on Monte Carlo simulations did not do better than just sticking with the crowd forecast in general, which often ran counter to the Monte Carlo sims. However, I concede that the sample size from which I'm drawing this conclusion is only 3 or 4 instances, which is not enough to render this conclusion foolproof.

Despite the planned adoption of BTC as legal tender, it seems regulatory issues could be THE dominant topic for the third quarter of 2021. It appears governments and their regulatory bodies can no longer dodge on crypto currencies but are expected to explain their stance towards them, which will reveal that there exist two opposing camps, a few that show moderate support of cryptos as they view it as an economically important area which offers opportunities for future growth (among them the U.S. who will want to lead the field before some other states will...), and a much bigger and growing camp of countries that fiercely oppose crypto currencies (reasons: strange and uncontrollable effects on fundamental economics mechanisms, ousting of central banks as an institution of sovereignity, criminal activity linked to payments in crypto currencies (drug trafficking, ransom cyber attacks,...), investment behavior of "retail investors" and risky instruments (Contracts for Difference), high leverage, little to no transparency and liability of exchanges, which may be part of a giant global tax evasion, money laundering scheme of the Asian sports betting mafia or other uptown white-collar organized crime.

I am absolutely convinced the next thing that will happen to bitcoin is that it will fall below $25k. The only question is when, and July 1 is fast approaching. Bitcoin has no use value in legitimate commerce for which there are no substitutes, that could lead to a higher bitcoin use value. There is a small chance that bitcoin could substitute for a percentage, e.g., 10 to 25 percent, of the gold that is held as a store of value. This would greatly increase Bitcoin's value. However, this is unlikely because bitcoin uses a lot of electricity just to remain in existence; bitcoin cannot be used for any non-commerce purpose, e.g., gold jewelry, electronics,; and, bitcoin is at least twice as volatile and therefore more risky on the downside. (Someone buying an asset as a store probably does not want much risk.)

To estimate the prob of falling below 25k, I looked at the peak-trough ratio of Jan 2018 to Feb 2018, as well as Feb 2020 to Mar 2020. The 2 ratios are 2.65 and 2.10. Assuming this season's peak has been 63k, it is possible that the retrospective trough from this season will be 63k / 2.65 = 23.8k < 25k. Since the previous drops occurred in 1 month, it also fits the July 1 time-frame for this forecast. However, Bitcoin is a much more financialized asset compared to those years, with the arrival of derivatives on BlockFI, KuCoin and elsewhere. I subjectively assume this provides a market mechanism to reduce the impact of a price fall by ~50%.

Broke below a support level around $45k, may keep going down. Prior research here suggested there's another support from orders placed around $28k though, and its hard to say if the dip will simply be bought again. The main yes case for below $25k is a narrative arising of the "digital gold" narrative being disproven by the recent volatility maybe attributable to Elon Musk. The issue is I don't know how much of the purchasing was people who actually believe in digital gold vs. people speculating on other people believing it, since both positions would encourage people to promote the idea in similar ways. There's also people speculating on Bitcoin because its volatile and conceptually simple. If the digital gold narrative being disproven becomes a narrative itself then it'd be a lot more impactful if most of the purchasing is speculative, people who actually believe in digital gold would probably be less phased by volatility (...it's Bitcoin, volatility isn't new). On the other hand speculation on other people's beliefs would probably be a lot more sensitive to new narratives since its all second-hand and its more difficult to think for people who aren't yourself.
